rey Maringira and Simbarashe Gukurume -- tPart Three. Popular Arts, Everyday Life, and the Politicization of Culture -- tChapter Eleven. Dressing en Style: Fashion and Fandom in Niger -- tChapter Twelve. The Revolution Lost: Generational Change and Urban Youth Logics in Conakry’s Dance Scene -- tChapter Thirteen. Culture Players and Poly-Ticks: Botswana Youth and Popular Culture Practices -- tChapter Fourteen #FeesMustFall and Youth Deconstruction of South Africa’s Liberation Narrative -- tAfterword: Young People and the Future of African Worlds -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the range of vibrant cultural production and political activism of youth in Africa today, as expressed through art, music, theater, and online media.This edited collection focuses on the links between youth and African popular culture. Contributions by a distinguished group of scholars explore popular culture produced and consumed by young people in contemporary Africa. Essays cover a variety of cultural representations--visual, oral, written, performative, fictional, social, and virtual--created by African youth, mostly about their lives and their immediate societies, and for themselves, but also consumed by the larger public and shared locally and globally. The volume examines the range of music, art, and media African youth produce, under what conditions or contexts they produce such work, and the aesthetic dimensions of these texts as cultural artifacts. Essays further explore why these textual practices matter as social facts, as interpretive acts, and as symbols of the cultural activism of young people in a rapidly changing world—a world where the global cultural economy is the prime terrain for the relentless struggles over the meanings that come to shape political-economic and social systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescrip